liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Retail trade in Australia has fallen by 0.8% in June, after a 0.8% rise in May and 0.1% fall in April. It means there was substantially less spending on mid-year sales (or end of financial year sales), and points to consumers feeling the pinch from cost-of-living pressures across the economy. "Retail turnover fell sharply in June due to weaker than usual spending on end of financial year sales ," said Ben Dorber, head of retail statistics for the ABS. "This comes as cost-of-living pressures continued to weigh on consumer spending. "There was extra discounting and promotional activity in May, leading up to mid-year sales events. "This delivered a boost in turnover for retailers, but that proved to be temporary as consumers pulled back on spending in June."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Retail spending falls 0.8pc in June as cost-of-living pressures bite

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Australian share market has opened lower on its final trading day of the week, down 0.8% to 7,394 points as of 10:30am AEST. (If it's live figures you're chasing, head to the post at the top of the blog, open it up and scroll down.) All sectors are in the red with the exception of consumer non-cyclicals, which is up 0.1%. Real estate and industrials are the worst performing sectors so far, down 1.4% and 1.3% respectively. Education is down 1.1%, and financials and basic materials have both dipped by 1%. The top five movers so far are: Megaport +1.8% Pro Medicus +1.8% New Hope Corporation +1.5% Medibank Private +1.1% NIB Holdings +1.1% And the bottom five movers right now are: Capricorn Metals -9.1% Silver Lake Resources -5.7% Regis Resources -5.6% Perseus Mining -5.6% West African Resources -5.3%

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Like most things, it depends who you ask — but NAB's economists are wanting to see a fall of 0.2% from the May figure with a softening in transaction data. NAB's economists are making that call given their Business Survey showed that the retail industry outlook has recently softened. Meanwhile the economists over at the Commonwealth Bank are forecasting a flat outcome for retail trade. Here's their reasoning: "While the May retail  figure was stronger than expected, this reflected the earlier timing of end  of financial year sales. " We expect some pullback occurred in June, but if  sales events stretched into later weeks, the pullback could instead occur  in July. "Our internal CBA card spending data indicate that retail spending  rose by 0.3% in June. "While our spending data closely tracks the official  ABS estimates, it has been slightly stronger of late. "This likely reflects  CBA banking a large share of new migrants, which adds to overall  spending on CBA cards."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: What would a 'good' retail sales figure in June look like?
